        "# Capital Structure Determinants: Testing Trade-off Theory vs Pecking Order Theory\n",
        "\n",
        "## Project Overview\n",
        "This notebook investigates the determinants of corporate capital structure using\n",
        "firm-level financial data derived from SEC filings (US-GAAP, XBRL format) of\n",
        "publicly listed United States companies since 2009.\n",
        "\n",
        "The objective is to test which of two classical capital structure theories\n",
        "better explains observed leverage patterns across firms:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Trade-off Theory: Firms select an optimal leverage level by balancing the\n",
        "   tax benefits of debt against the costs of financial distress. This theory\n",
        "   predicts a positive relationship between profitability and leverage, since\n",
        "   more profitable firms can support more debt.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Pecking Order Theory: Firms prefer internal financing first, then debt,\n",
        "   and equity issuance as a last resort. This theory predicts a negative\n",
        "   relationship between profitability and leverage, since profitable firms\n",
        "   generate more retained earnings and rely less on external debt.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Dataset\n",
        "Name: Financial Statement Data Sets (Company Facts)\n",
        "Source: Kaggle, derived from SEC EDGAR company facts filings\n",
        "Link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/vadimvanak/company-facts-2\n",
        "Content: US-GAAP financial statement data extracted from SEC filings of listed\n",
        "United States companies, covering periods since January 2009. The dataset\n",
        "contains firm-level financial statement line items such as assets,\n",
        "liabilities, equity, revenue, and net income, which will be used to construct\n",
        "the variables required for this analysis.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Project Steps\n",
        "1. Set up the environment and download the dataset from Kaggle\n",
        "2. Inspect the raw dataset structure and identify relevant financial fields\n",
        "3. Construct firm-level variables: leverage, profitability, tangibility, size, and growth\n",
        "4. Clean the dataset and handle missing values or outliers\n",
        "5. Conduct descriptive statistics and exploratory data analysis\n",
        "6. Visualize leverage patterns across firms and sectors\n",
        "7. Run regression analysis of leverage on its determinants\n",
        "8. Interpret results in light of Trade-off versus Pecking Order predictions\n",
        "9. Summarize findings and conclude the project"
      ]
    },
