        "\n",
        "The raw dataset consisted of 79,448,144 individual XBRL financial statement\n",
        "line items across 9,641 unique tags. This was filtered to six core tags\n",
        "required for the analysis, merged with filing metadata, restricted to\n",
        "annual filings, deduplicated to remove comparative prior-year figures, and\n",
        "corrected to exclude quarterly values embedded within annual filings. This\n",
        "process produced a clean panel of 9,733 firm-year observations across\n",
        "approximately 6,600 unique companies.\n",
        "\n",
        "Five variables were constructed for the analysis: Leverage, Profitability,\n",
        "Tangibility, Size, and Revenue Growth. After addressing implausible values\n",
        "and winsorizing extreme observations, descriptive statistics, correlation\n",
        "analysis, and two ordinary least squares regression models were used to\n",
        "examine the relationship between these variables.\n",
        "\n",
        "The central finding of this analysis is a consistently negative and\n",
        "statistically significant relationship between Profitability and Leverage\n",
        "across both model specifications, with coefficients of -0.2305 and -0.3425\n",
        "respectively. This finding is more consistent with Pecking Order Theory,\n",
        "which predicts that profitable firms rely more heavily on internal\n",
        "financing and less on debt, than with Trade-off Theory, which predicts a\n",
        "positive relationship between profitability and leverage.\n",
        "\n",
        "Tangibility and Size showed positive relationships with Leverage in the\n",
        "larger sample, consistent with the intuition that firms with more\n",
        "collateralizable assets and larger firms tend to carry more debt, although\n",
        "these effects were not statistically significant in the smaller sample\n",
        "that included Revenue Growth. Revenue Growth itself showed no significant\n",
        "relationship with Leverage.\n",
        "\n",
        "Sector-level analysis further showed that average Leverage varies\n",
        "meaningfully across industries, ranging from approximately 0.54 to 0.76,\n",
        "indicating that industry classification captures financing patterns not\n",
        "fully explained by firm-level variables alone.\n",
